{{For|the artist Eikyū (''{{nihongo2|瑛九}}'')|Ei-Q}}
{{History of Japan|Shoso-in.jpg| Image explanation = [[Shōsōin]]}}

{{nihongo|'''Eikyū'''|永久}} was a {{nihongo|[[Japanese era name]]|年号,|''nengō'',|lit. "year name"}} after ''[[Ten'ei]]'' and before ''[[Gen'ei]].''  This period spanned the years from July 1113 through April 1118.<ref>Nussbaum, Louis-Frédéric. (2005). "''Eikyū''" in {{Google books|p2QnPijAEmEC|''Japan Encyclopedia'', p. 171|page=171}}; n.b., Louis-Frédéric is pseudonym of Louis-Frédéric Nussbaum, ''see'' [https://archive.is/20120524174828/http://dispatch.opac.ddb.de/DB=4.1/PPN?PPN=128842709 Deutsche Nationalbibliothek Authority File].</ref> The reigning emperor was {{nihongo|[[Emperor Toba]]''-tennō''|鳥羽天皇}}.<ref>Titsingh, Isaac. (1834). [https://books.google.com/books?id=18oNAAAAIAAJ&pg=PP9&dq=nipon+o+dai+itsi+ran#PRA1-PA178,M1  ''Annales des empereurs du Japon'', pp. 178]-180; Brown, Delmer ''et al.'' (1979). ''Gukanshō'', p. 321; Varley, H. Paul. (1980). ''Jinnō Shōtōki'', pp. 200-204.</ref>

==Change of Era==
* '''January 20, 1113''' {{nihongo|''Eikyū gannen''|永久元年}}<!-- NengoCalc 永久一年一月一日 -->: The new era name was created to mark an event or series of events. The previous era ended and the new one commenced in ''Ten'ei'' 4, on the thirteenth day of the seventh month of 1113.<ref>Brown, p. 321.</ref>

==Events of the ''Eikyū'' Era==
* '''1113''' (''Eikyū 1, 4th month''): Fujiwara Tadasane was named ''[[kampaku]]''.<ref name="t179">Titsingh, [https://books.google.com/books?id=18oNAAAAIAAJ&pg=PP9&dq=nipon+o+dai+itsi+ran#PRA1-PA179,M1  p. 179.]</ref>
* '''1113''' (''Eikyū 1, 4th month''): Emperor Toba visited the  [[Matsunoo Shrine]] and the [[Kitano Tenman-gū]]. When the emperor visits  [[Shinto]] shrines,  it is always a pleasure party for him. Without this pretext, court etiquette did not permit him to leave the palace.<ref name="t179"/>
* '''1113''' (''Eikyū 1, 10th month''): Toba visited the temples on [[Mount Hiei]] in the vicinity of Kyoto.<ref name="t179"/>
* '''1113''' (''Eikyū 1, 11th month ''): Toba visited the [[Inari Shrine]] and the [[Yasaka Shrine|Gion Shrine]].<ref name="t179"/>

