[[File:JacquesBernard.jpg|thumb|Jacques Bernard]]
'''Jacques Bernard''' (1 September 1658 – 27 April 1718), [[France|French]] [[theologian]] and publicist, who lived his entire academic career in the [[Dutch Republic]].

==Life==
He was born at [[Nyons]] in [[Dauphiné]].
Having studied at [[Geneva]], he returned to France in 1679, and was chosen minister of [[Venterol, Drôme|Venterol]] in Dauphiné. He moved to the church of [[Vinsobres]]. As he continued to preach the reformed doctrines (in opposition to the royal ordinance) he was obliged to leave the country and retired to Holland, where he was appointed one of the pensionary ministers of [[Gouda, South Holland|Gouda]]. In July 1686 he began publishing the ''Histoire abregée de l'Europe'' which he continued, monthly, till December 1688. {{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}

In 1692 he began his ''Lettres historiques'', containing an account of the most important events in Europe. He carried on this work till the end of 1688. When [[Jean Leclerc (theologian)|Le Clerc]] discontinued his ''Bibliothèque universelle'' in 1691, Bernard wrote the greater part of the twentieth volume and the five following volumes. In 1698 he collected and published ''Actes et mémoires des négociations de la paix Ryswick'', in four volumes 12mo.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}

In 1699 he began a continuation of [[Pierre Bayle|Bayle]]'s ''[[Nouvelles de la republique des lettres]]'', which continued till December 1710. In 1705 he was unanimously elected one of the ministers of the Walloon church at [[Leiden]]; and about the same time he succeeded [[Burchard de Volder|de Volder]] in the chair of philosophy and mathematics at [[university of Leiden|Leiden]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}} From 1712 until 1718 he was a [[full professor]] at the University of Leiden.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hoogleraren.leidenuniv.nl/id/164 |title=Jacques Bernard |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |website= |publisher=Universitaire Bibliotheken Leiden |access-date=15 November 2015 |quote=}}</ref>

In 1716 he published a supplement to [[Louis Moréri|Moréri]]'s dictionary, in two volumes folio. The same year he resumed his ''Nouvelles de la république des lettres'', and continued it till his death. Besides the works above mentioned, he was the author of two practical treatises, one on late [[repentance]] (1712), the other on the excellence of religion (1714).{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}

